<h2 id="overview">1. Overview &amp; rationale</h2>
<p>
For actuator <strong>system identification</strong> on the twin-rotor tailsitter we need a clean, repeatable
<em>chirp</em> (swept-frequency sine) driving one control axis at a time, with the rotors held at a fixed RPM, so the
open-loop actuator / airframe frequency response can be measured. Normally
<code>mc_att_control</code> &rarr; <code>mc_rate_control</code> produce the torque/thrust setpoints that the control
allocator turns into actuator commands. This feature <strong>replaces</strong> those setpoints with a generated chirp,
bypassing the attitude/rate controllers entirely.
</p>
<p>
The injection lives in <code>ActuatorEffectivenessTwinRotorTailsitter::updateSetpoint()</code>. For this airframe the
effectiveness <em>matrix</em> is all-zeros (motors and servos are added with empty axis vectors in
<code>getEffectivenessMatrix()</code>), so <code>updateSetpoint()</code> is the single authoritative stage that computes
<em>every</em> motor and servo output from the 6-axis control setpoint. Injecting there gives full, clean control of the
outputs while reusing the existing swashplate / elevon geometry.
</p>

<!-- ===================================================================== -->
<h2 id="flow">2. How it works (data flow)</h2>

<p><strong>Normal path:</strong></p>
<div class="flow">
  <div class="box dim">attitude / rate<br>controllers</div><span class="arr">&rarr;</span>
  <div class="box dim">torque + thrust<br>setpoint</div><span class="arr">&rarr;</span>
  <div class="box">ControlAllocator</div><span class="arr">&rarr;</span>
  <div class="box hl">updateSetpoint()</div><span class="arr">&rarr;</span>
  <div class="box">actuator_motors<br>actuator_servos</div>
</div>

<p><strong>Chirp path</strong> (<code>CA_CHIRP_MODE &ne; 0</code>, armed):</p>
<div class="flow">
  <div class="box dim" style="text-decoration:line-through">controllers</div><span class="arr">&times;</span>
  <div class="box hl">Chirp generator<br><span class="small">(elapsed time t)</span></div><span class="arr">&rarr;</span>
  <div class="box hl">applyChirp()<br><span class="small">zero sp · drive 1 axis</span></div><span class="arr">&rarr;</span>
  <div class="box hl">updateSetpoint()<br><span class="small">swashplate / elevon map</span></div><span class="arr">&rarr;</span>
  <div class="box">actuators</div>
</div>

<p>
When the chirp is active, the incoming control setpoint is copied to a local vector, <strong>zeroed</strong> (full MC
bypass), and the chirp value is written onto the selected axis. The rotors are held at <code>CA_CHIRP_RPM</code> (or
swept, for the RPM chirp). The rest of <code>updateSetpoint()</code> — the body&rarr;rotor transform, swashplate
geometry and elevon mixing — runs unchanged on that vector. When <code>CA_CHIRP_MODE = 0</code> the original code path
is byte-for-byte unchanged.
</p>

<!-- ===================================================================== -->
<h2 id="equation">3. The chirp equation</h2>
<p>
A polynomial frequency sweep. The instantaneous frequency rises from <code>freq_init</code> to <code>freq_final</code>
over the duration <code>total_time</code> following a polynomial of order <code>chirp_order</code>. The running elapsed
time <code>t</code> sweeps <code>0 &rarr; T</code>.
</p>

<div class="formula">
  <div class="lbl">sweep coefficient</div>
  &beta; = ( f<sub>1</sub> &minus; f<sub>0</sub> ) / T<sup>k</sup>
</div>
<div class="formula">
  <div class="lbl">output</div>
  out(t) = A &middot; sin( 2&pi; &middot; ( &beta;/(k+1) &middot; t<sup>(k+1)</sup> &nbsp;+&nbsp; f<sub>0</sub> &middot; t ) )
</div>

<p class="small">
where <code>f<sub>0</sub>=freq_init</code>, <code>f<sub>1</sub>=freq_final</code>, <code>k=chirp_order</code>,
<code>T=total_time</code>, <code>A=amp</code>. Instantaneous frequency is <code>&beta;&middot;t<sup>k</sup>+f<sub>0</sub></code>,
so it sweeps <em>exactly</em> <code>f<sub>0</sub>&rarr;f<sub>1</sub></code> over <code>T</code>. <code>k=1</code> is the
classic linear chirp; at <code>t=0</code> the output is 0 (smooth start).
</p>

<div class="note">
  <b>Note on the original formula</b>
  The request wrote <code>beta = (f1-f0)*total_time^k</code> and used <code>total_time</code> inside the sine. The sine
  argument must use the <em>running</em> time <code>t</code> (not the constant duration), and <code>beta</code> needs
  <code>&divide;T<sup>k</sup></code> (not <code>&times;</code>) for the sweep to actually reach <code>freq_final</code> at
  <code>t=T</code>. This corrected, standard form was confirmed before implementing.
</div>

<pre><code><span class="tok-c">// Chirp.hpp — the core logic, pure & deterministic (no dependence on hrt)</span>
<span class="tok-k">float</span> <span class="tok-f">update</span>(<span class="tok-k">float</span> t) <span class="tok-k">const</span>
{
    <span class="tok-k">if</span> (_total_time &lt;= <span class="tok-n">0.f</span>) {
        <span class="tok-k">return</span> <span class="tok-n">0.f</span>;
    }
    <span class="tok-k">const float</span> tc    = math::<span class="tok-f">constrain</span>(t, <span class="tok-n">0.f</span>, _total_time);
    <span class="tok-k">const float</span> beta  = (_freq_final - _freq_init) / <span class="tok-f">powf</span>(_total_time, _chirp_order);
    <span class="tok-k">const float</span> phase = <span class="tok-n">2.f</span> * <span class="tok-n">M_PI_F</span> * (beta / (_chirp_order + <span class="tok-n">1.f</span>) * <span class="tok-f">powf</span>(tc, _chirp_order + <span class="tok-n">1.f</span>) + _freq_init * tc);
    <span class="tok-k">return</span> _amplitude * <span class="tok-f">sinf</span>(phase);
}</code></pre>

