<h2 id="behavior">7. Behavior notes &amp; safety</h2>
<div class="warn">
  <b>Armed only, one-shot</b>
  The sweep starts on the first armed frame after the chirp is enabled and returns to baseline after
  <code>CA_CHIRP_T</code> seconds. Disarming (or toggling <code>CA_CHIRP_MODE</code>) re-arms the one-shot so it replays.
</div>
<ul>
  <li><b>Full MC bypass.</b> While active, the rate/attitude controller output is ignored — only the chirp drives the selected axis; all others are held at baseline.</li>
  <li><b>Cyclic / roll chirps pass through the body&rarr;rotor gains</b> (<code>CA_TWIN*_B2R_*</code>), so the effective servo amplitude is scaled by those. During them the collective sits at its swashplate trim (<code>CA_TWIN*_B2R_Z_0</code>) and the motors are held at <code>CA_CHIRP_RPM</code>.</li>
  <li><b>RPM units.</b> <code>CA_CHIRP_RPM</code> is the <em>normalized motor command</em> that corresponds to ~6000 rpm on your hardware (the motor output, not a physical rpm number).</li>
  <li><b>No change when off.</b> With <code>CA_CHIRP_MODE = 0</code> the actuator outputs are identical to the stock throttle-curve behavior (guarded by a regression test).</li>
</ul>

