<h3>8.3 — SITL spot-check (end-to-end)</h3>
<p>Run a twin-rotor-tailsitter SITL model, then in the <code>pxh&gt;</code> shell:</p>
<pre><code><span class="tok-c"># select the airframe and a cyclic-pitch chirp at a held rotor speed</span>
param set CA_AIRFRAME  <span class="tok-n">11</span>
param set CA_CHIRP_MODE <span class="tok-n">1</span>      <span class="tok-c"># 1 = cyclic pitch</span>
param set CA_CHIRP_AMP  <span class="tok-n">0.2</span>
param set CA_CHIRP_F0   <span class="tok-n">0.5</span>
param set CA_CHIRP_F1   <span class="tok-n">15</span>
param set CA_CHIRP_T    <span class="tok-n">20</span>
param set CA_CHIRP_ORD  <span class="tok-n">1</span>
param set CA_CHIRP_RPM  <span class="tok-n">0.6</span>    <span class="tok-c"># normalized motor cmd = your ~6000 rpm point</span>

<span class="tok-c"># arm, then watch the outputs</span>
listener actuator_servos     <span class="tok-c"># cyclic/collective servos sweeping</span>
listener actuator_motors     <span class="tok-c"># motors held at CA_CHIRP_RPM (or sweeping in RPM mode)</span></code></pre>
<p>
Confirm: the swept axis oscillates with increasing frequency over <code>CA_CHIRP_T</code>; the motors stay at
<code>CA_CHIRP_RPM</code> for cyclic/collective modes; output returns to baseline after <code>T</code> (re-arm to repeat).
For analysis, log <code>actuator_motors</code> / <code>actuator_servos</code> to a <code>.ulog</code> and plot the response.
